\date{2025-02-03}
\title{Fibration classifier}
\author{samtoth}

\import{basic-macros}

\p{
For each universe #{\mathcal{U}}, there is a type #{\mathcal{S} :^{\flat} \mathcal{U}}, with an embedding #{\mathcal{S} \hookrightarrow \mathcal{U}} such that for any #{P : A \to \mathcal{S}}, the composite map into #{\mathcal{U}} is [covariant](st-0008). It has the universal property that any covariant map #{P : A \to \mathcal{U}} factors through #{\mathcal{S}}.
}


\subtree{
\taxon{lemma}
\p{The type #{S^\mathbb{I}} is equivalent to #{\Sigma_{A,B :^\flat S} B^A}.}

\proof{
   We construct a map first, given an #{f : \mathbb{I} \to \mathcal{S}}, we can compose with #{\iota : \mathcal{S \to U}}, to obtain a covariant fibration #{\mathbb{I} \to \mathcal{U}}. In particular for the unique #{Hom_{\mathcal{I}}(0,1)}, we have the function #{(X : P(0)) \to \mathrm{isContr}((Y : P(1)) \times Hom^P_{0\to1}(X, Y))}, and so we can just precompose with the projection to obtain a map #{P(0) \to P(1)}. The fact it is an equivalence can be derrived from the fact it is contractible.
}
}

